-- Roman Pack Pedia
insert or replace into LocalizedText (Language, Tag, Text) values
-- Ragusa
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "Traditional historiography suggests that Ragusa, or Dubrovnik as it is known today, was founded by the Romans and Dalmatians in the 7th century AD to escape Slavic invasion, but modern archaeological findings suggest that the ancient Greeks used it as a midway port."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "传统史学认为，拉古萨，也就是今天的杜布罗夫尼克（Dubrovnik）是公元7世纪时罗马人和达尔马提亚人（Dalmatians）为了躲避斯拉夫人入侵建立的，但是现代考古发现指出，古希腊人就把这里当做中途港使用了。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "The region of the Dalmatian coast where Ragusa is located came under Eastern Roman control after the fall of the Ostrogothic Kingdom. Thanks to the city's own good harbour and the limited control of the Eastern Roman Empire, Ragusa was already a virtually autonomous city-state during this period. After the Fourth Crusade, Ragusa became one of the Venetian possessions in Dalmatia."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "拉古萨所在的达尔马提亚海岸地区在东哥特王国灭亡之后就处于东罗马的控制之下。得益于这个城市自身良好的港口条件和东罗马帝国有限的控制力，在这一时期拉古萨已经是实际上自治的城邦。在第四次十字军之后，拉古萨成为威尼斯在达尔马提亚的属地之一。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "In 1301 the Hungarian Angevin dynasty replaced the Arpad dynasty. The Croatian nobles who had supported the Hungarian kings of the Angevin dynasty wanted the Hungarian crown to help them expel the Venetian forces from the Dalmatian coast. The result of the Hungarian-Venetian war was the Peace Treaty of Zadar, which gave Ragusa full independence from Venetian rule and made it a city-state republic. Ragusa's good position as a midway port on the sea route between the Eastern Mediterranean and Italy led to its rapid rise to power, and in the 15th and 16th centuries it became, under Ottoman protection, the only republic in the Mediterranean at the time to rival Venice."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "1301年匈牙利的安茹王朝取代了阿帕德王朝。而扶持了安茹王朝匈牙利王的克罗地亚贵族们就希望匈牙利王室帮助他们驱逐达尔马提亚海岸的威尼斯势力。匈牙利与威尼斯战争的结果就是《扎达尔和平条约》，这个条约使拉古萨完全从威尼斯统治下独立，成为了一个城邦共和国。作为东地中海与意大利海上航线的中途港，拉古萨良好的位置使其迅速崛起，15-16世纪中，拉古萨在奥斯曼的保护下成为了当时地中海上唯一可以匹敌威尼斯的共和国。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "The Republic of Ragusa cherishes freedom in its culture, where Latin, Dalmatian and Slavic cultures merged and where Croatian culture emerged. Although its status has been greatly diminished by the decline of the Mediterranean trade, Ragusa remains a Croatian cultural and tourist destination."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_RAGUSA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "拉古萨共和国在文化上珍视自由，拉丁、达尔马提亚和斯拉夫文化在此融合，克罗地亚文化在此产生。虽然其地位因为地中海贸易的衰落大不如前，但是拉古萨依旧是克罗地亚文化和旅游胜地。"),
-- Prague
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "The Bohemian name comes from the Celtic tribe of the Boii, while the Czechs are the main group of Western Slavs. According to the Eastern Roman historian Prokopios, Slavs existed in this area until around 512."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "波西米亚一名来自凯尔特人的波西部落，而捷克则是西斯拉夫人的主要的一支。据东罗马历史学家普罗科匹乌斯记载，至512年前后此地已经存在斯拉夫人了。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "According to Czech legend, Princess Libuse, a chieftainess of a Czech tribe, married the farmer Premysl to stabilise the tribe and founded the Premyslid dynasty, the first feudal dynasty in the Czech Republic. In legend, Princess Libuse foresaw a prosperous city and founded Prague."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "据捷克传说记载，捷克部落的女酋长利布丝公主为了稳定部落嫁给了农夫培密索尔，建立了捷克第一个封建王朝培密索利德王朝。在传说中，利布丝公主预见了一座繁荣的城市，于是建立了布拉格。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "Prague is located on the banks of the Vltava River, a major transport route, and was built around a castle in the early days. During the Middle Ages, the Czech Republic was involved in the political activities of the Holy Roman Empire, mainly as a Bohemian kingdom. In the 13th century three settlements around Prague Castle were given municipal privileges, and in 1257 a new small town (Mala Strana) was built to the south of Prague Castle, an area inhabited by Germans with the right to self-government. The district of Prague Castle (Hradčany), immediately to the west and north of the castle, was granted autonomy in 1320. The old town of Prague (Stare Mesto), across the Vltava, was granted autonomy in 1230."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "布拉格处在伏尔塔瓦河畔的交通要道，在早期是围绕着城堡建立的。在中世纪，捷克主要作为波西米亚王国参与神圣罗马帝国的政治活动。因为其沟通南北的地理位置，布拉格的工商业开始发展，吸引了许多犹太人。13世纪，在布拉格城堡周围的3个居民点获得了市镇的特权。1257年，在布拉格城堡以南新建了小城，这是德意志人居住的地区，拥有自治权。紧邻城堡西面和北面的布拉格城堡区在1320年获得自治权。伏尔塔瓦河对面的布拉格老城则早在1230年就已获得自治权。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "Prague reached its peak in the 14th century under the reign of Charles IV of the Luxembourg dynasty of the Holy Roman Empire. Charles IV, the eldest son of a Czech princess and John of Luxembourg, was born in Prague in 1316 and became King of Bohemia on his father's death in 1346. As a result of his campaign, the diocese of Prague was elevated to an archdiocese in 1344, and in 1355 Charles was crowned in Rome and became Holy Roman Emperor. Prague became the administrative centre of the Holy Roman Empire. Charles wanted Prague to be one of the most beautiful cities in the world. He made Prague the most splendid city within the Empire, and the most prominent building in the city is the Cathedral of St. Vitus, first adopted in Central Europe in the grand Gothic style, with an interior decorated in an independent artistic style known as Bohemian.On 7 April 1348 he founded the first university in Central, Northern and Eastern Europe, today known as Univerzita Karlova, the oldest university in the Czech Republic and once the first university in Germany. In the same year he also built the new city of Prague (Nove Město) next to the old town and erected the Charles Bridge between the new city and the small town. He also built many new churches. At the time, Prague was the third largest city in Europe, had a mint and was home to German and Italian merchants and bankers."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "14世纪，布拉格在神圣罗马帝国卢森堡王朝的查理四世统治下达到鼎盛时期。查理四世是捷克公主和卢森堡的约翰的长子，于1316年出生在布拉格，1346年当他父亲去世时成为波希米亚国王。由于他的争取，布拉格教区在1344年升格为总教区。1355年，查理在罗马加冕，成为神圣罗马帝国皇帝。布拉格成为神圣罗马帝国的行政中心。查理希望布拉格成为世界上最美丽的城市之一。他将布拉格建成帝国境内最为辉煌的城市，而位于该市最为显赫的建筑就是圣维特主教座堂，在中欧首先采用了宏伟的哥特式，室内装饰采用了独立的艺术风格，被称为波希米亚风格。1348年4月7日，他建立了中欧、北欧和东欧的第一所大学，今天称为查理大学，是捷克最古老的大学，也曾是德国第一所大学。同年，他还在老城的旁边建立了布拉格新城，并在新城和小城之间架起了查理大桥。他还新建了许多教堂。当时，布拉格是欧洲的第三大城市，拥有一个造币厂，德国和意大利的商人和银行家聚集于此。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "The Reformation was a period of Czech lamentation. from 1402, Jan Hus, a professor of theology at Charles University, preached in Czech in the chapel of Bethlehem, allowing the common people to receive the Eucharist and the Holy Blood with the clergy, and was condemned as a heretic by the Holy See and executed by fire in Constance on 6 July 1415. four years later, the first window-throwing incident in Prague led to the Hus War. The Huss Wars. Huss came from a poor background and stood firmly by the side of the working people. He stood up for the principles of Christian equality, opposed the arrogance of the Roman Church, opposed the atonement bill and preached in the Czech language. He was executed by the Church for this, but his death ignited the pent-up resentment of the Czech people against the Church and ignited the Hussite Wars. The Huss Wars were the precursor of the European national liberation movement, in which for the first time there was an organised and conscious army that broke away from the feudal system and Hussite Wagon emerged to counter the heavy cavalry of the chivalric class. The Hussite War as a peasant war failed and the Hussite War as a Czech national liberation movement triumphed. Czech national consciousness began to take shape in this period."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "宗教改革是捷克人慷慨悲歌的时期。1402年起，查理大学的神学教授胡斯在伯利恒小教堂用捷克语布道，让平民信徒与神职人员同领圣体和圣血，而被教庭裁定为异端，1415年7月6日在康斯坦茨处以火刑。4年以后，布拉格发生第一次掷出窗外事件，引发了胡斯战争。胡斯出身贫苦，坚定的站在劳动人民的身边。他坚持基督教的平等原则，反对罗马教会的骄奢淫逸，反对赎罪券，用捷克语布道。他因此被教会处死，但是他的死点燃了捷克人民对教会的积怨，点燃了胡斯战争。胡斯战争是欧洲民族解放运动的先声，在其中，第一次出现有组织、有觉悟的脱离了封建制度的军队，出现了反制骑士阶级重骑兵的战车兵。作为农民战争的胡斯战争失败了，作为捷克民族解放运动的胡斯战争胜利了。捷克的民族意识在这一时期开始形成。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "After the subsequent civil strife in the Holy Roman Empire and the Thirty Years' War, the Czech Republic came under the control of the Austrian Habsburgs. The devastation caused by the Thirty Years' War caused a period of depression, but Prague continued to develop in the 18th century. The Czech Republic became the main industrial region of the Austro-Hungarian Empire during the Industrial Revolution because of its rich coal and iron resources, and Prague became the industrial centre of the Austro-Hungarian Empire and the most developed capitalist economy within the Austro-Hungarian Empire, and Czech nationalism was shaken by the European Spring Revolution of 1848, which was unsuccessful but gave the Czech Republic some of its rights."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "在后续的神圣罗马帝国内乱和三十年战争之后，捷克处于奥地利哈布斯堡王朝的控制之下。三十年战争造成的破坏使布拉格萧条了一段时间，但是在18世纪布拉格还是得以继续发展。因为捷克煤铁资源丰富，在工业革命中捷克成为了奥匈帝国主要的工业地区，布拉格则成为了奥匈帝国的工业中心，捷克也成为了奥匈帝国内部资本主义经济最发达的地区。1848年欧洲之春革命中捷克民族主义也大为震动，虽然他们的起义没有成功，但是还是是捷克获得了部分权利。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7", "In World War I the Austro-Hungarian Empire collapsed and the Czech Republic became the capital of an independent Czechoslovakia. In World War II Czechoslovakia was occupied and after the war it was placed under Soviet control. The Czech Republic initially copied the Soviet model, but growing political problems led Czech leader Aleksander Dubček to enact a series of reforms in 1968, known as the Prague Spring, but the Soviet Union did not want to see such freedom for the Czech Republic. In August 1986, the Warsaw Pact intervened in Czech internal affairs and entered Prague to arrest Dubček, and the reforms were suspended."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7", "在一战中奥匈帝国解体，捷克成为了独立的捷克斯洛伐克的首都。在二战中捷克被占领，战后又被划为苏联控制区。捷克最初也复制了苏联模式，但是政治上越来越多的问题使得捷克领导人亚历山大·杜布切克在1968年颁布了一系列改革措施，也就是“布拉格之春”，然而苏联不愿意看到捷克拥有如此大的自由。1986年8月，华约武装干涉捷克内政，进入布拉格逮捕杜布切克，改革中止。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_8", "From the Hussite War to the Prague Spring, the burden of history has weighed heavily on this crossroads of Europe, the industrial and cultural heart of the Czech nation. Throughout their history, the Czechs have faced a treacherous and often unsuccessful struggle against the Powers, but none of this has shaken the determination of the Czech people to resist tyranny."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_PRAGUE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_8", "从胡斯起义到布拉格之春，历史的重担沉甸甸地压在这欧洲大陆的十字路口，这捷克民族的工业和文化心脏上。捷克人在历史上一直面临列强环伺的险恶处境，他们的反抗时常无法成功，但是这一切都没有磨灭捷克人民反抗暴政的决心。"),
-- Florence
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "The Italian word 'Firenze' is the English word for 'Florence', a name that represents Italy's most glorious and prosperous city republic."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "意大利语“翡冷翠”即英语中的“佛罗伦萨”，这个名字代表着意大利最为辉煌繁荣的城邦共和国。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "The area of Tuscany where Florence is located has been settled since the time of the Etruscan culture, and the historical record shows that Florence was a Roman colony founded under Julius Caesar, meaning 'flowering' (Florentia). After the fall of Western Rome, the area was ruled in turn by the Eastern Gothic, Eastern Roman, Lombard and Frankish regimes, and in 774 Florence became the territory of the Duchy of Tuscany, with Lucca as its capital. The city was a trading commune until 1000 AD, when Margrave Hugh 'the Great' of Tuscany moved to Florence, ushering in the city's golden age."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "佛罗伦萨所在的托斯卡纳地区早在伊特拉斯坎文化时期已经有了定居点，历史记载中的佛罗伦萨是凯撒时期建立的一个罗马殖民地，意为“繁花绽放”。西罗马灭亡后，东哥特、东罗马、伦巴底、法兰克这几个政权轮番统治了这一地区，到公元774年，以卢卡为首都的托斯卡纳公国建立，佛罗伦萨成为其领土。这个城市之前一直是从事贸易的公社，直到公元1000年，托斯卡纳侯爵“伟大者”雨果迁都佛罗伦萨，开启了佛罗伦萨的黄金时代。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "From 1115 Florence became an autonomous medieval commune and in 1252 a republic. By this time Florence had become one of the banking centres of Europe, with a large number of banks based here and trading destinations as far away as Bruges in the Netherland. Florence's trade exports led to a shift in the currency of Europe from silver bullion to a variety of issued currencies. In 1293, Florence adopted the Ordinances of Justice, which regulated the republican system of government. By the 14th century, after the Black Death and the Revolt of the Ciompi (wool weavers), the city's power had effectively fallen into the hands of the Albizzi family, and then the Medici family. By the time of Lorenzo de' Medici, the Medici family's energies were spent on patronising the arts, with Michelangelo, Leonardo da Vinci and Botticelli all working in Florence during this period. By 1494, King Charles VIII of France had invaded Italy in an attempt to incorporate Tuscany into the territory he claimed as the Kingdom of Naples. The rulers of the Medici family at the time hoped to surrender to preserve themselves, but this provoked the wrath of the citizens, who expelled the Medici from Florence and re-established the republic. However, the Medici family was restored to power in 1527. Much of what we know about Florence comes from the Florentine Histories written by Niccolo Machiavelli during this period. 1530 saw the fall of Florence to Spain, which made the Medici hereditary dukes and devastated the city's facilities and economy."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "自1115年开始，佛罗伦萨成为了一个自治公社，1252年成立共和国。此时佛罗伦萨已经成为欧洲的银行业中心之一，大量银行本部就在此地，贸易目的地远达尼德兰的布鲁日。佛罗伦萨的贸易输出使得欧洲的通货由银块转为各种各样的发行货币。这一时期，意大利政局长期动荡，佛罗伦萨也在比萨、热那亚之间辗转寻求庇护，但是这并不影响佛罗伦萨的经济。1293年，佛罗伦萨通过了正义法规，规范了共和国政体。到14世纪的黑死病和羊毛纺织工人起义之后，城市政权实际上落入奥比齐家族手中，然后又落入美第奇家族手中。到洛伦佐·德·美第奇时期，美第奇家族的精力都花在赞助艺术上，这一时期米开朗基罗、达·芬奇、波提切利都在佛罗伦萨创作。到1494年，法王查理八世入侵意大利，试图将托斯卡纳纳入他宣称的那不勒斯王国领土。当时的美第奇家族统治者希望投降来保全自己，但是这引起了市民的愤怒，于是佛罗伦萨市民驱逐了美第奇家族，重建了共和制。然而，美第奇家族在1527年重建了政权。我们对佛罗伦萨的很多了解都来自这一时期马基雅维利写的《佛罗伦萨史》。1530年，西班牙攻陷了佛罗伦萨，使得美第奇家族成为世袭公爵，并且极大的破坏了城市设施和经济。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "Florence's place in the cultural history of medieval Europe is significant. She was the birthplace of the Renaissance, in which she was to Athens what Athens was to classical Greece. Its high status as an important literary centre in Italian history led to the Tuscan dialect becoming the basis of the standard Italian language. During the unification of Italy, Florence also became the temporary capital of the country. To this day, Florence remains culturally important."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_FLORENCE_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "佛罗伦萨在欧洲中世纪文化史上的地位举足轻重。她是文艺复兴的发源地，在文艺复兴中她的地位如图雅典之于古典希腊。作为意大利历史上重要的文学中心，其崇高地位使得托斯卡纳方言成为标准意大利语的基础。在意大利统一的过程中，佛罗伦萨还曾经成为意大利的临时首都。时至今日，佛罗伦萨在文化上的地位依旧举足轻重。"),
-- Gundishapur
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "On the edge of a small village in Khuzestan, Iran, lies Gundeshapur, the highest academic centre of the Sassanid Empire."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "在伊朗胡齐斯坦的一个小村庄边上，埋藏着萨珊波斯的最高学术中心贡德沙普尔。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "In 256 AD, Shapur I, King of Kings (Shahanshah) of Sassanid Persia, defeated Rome and conquered Antioch. Shapur took his captured Roman soldiers and built a new city between Susa and Shushtar, Gundeshapur, which means 'fortress of Shapur'. This became the new capital of Sassan."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "公元256年，萨珊波斯的万王之王沙普尔一世大破罗马，攻克安条克。沙普尔将他俘获的罗马士兵带到苏萨和舒适塔尔之间建立了一座新城，这就是贡德沙普尔，意为“沙普尔之城”，沙普尔王就此住了下来，这里就此成为萨珊的新都城。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "As Eastern Rome began to expel Nestorian and Pagan scholars, Gundeshapur became the new centre of classical scholarship in the West Asian-Mediterranean world. By the time of Khosrow I (531-579), Gundeshapur had become one of the most important cities of higher education in the world. A large number of texts in Greek and Syriac were translated into Middle Persian (Pahlavi), covering a wide range of subjects, mainly astronomy, astrology, medicine, philosophy and various crafts. Chinese and Indian texts from the East are also gathered here."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "随着东罗马开始驱逐聂斯托利派和多神教学者，贡德沙普尔成为了西亚-地中海世界新的古典学术中心。到霍斯劳一世（531-579）时期，贡德沙普尔已经成为世界上最重要的高等教育城市之一。大量希腊语和叙利亚语言的文献被翻译为中古波斯语，其内容包罗万象，主要是天文学、占星学、医学、哲学和各种工艺技巧。东方的中国和印度文献也在此汇集。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "After the Islamic conquest of Sassanid Persia in 638, Gundeshapur went into decline and has not been found in the historical records since 869."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_GUNDISHAPUR_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "638年伊斯兰征服萨珊波斯之后，贡德沙普尔就开始走向衰落，自869年之后，贡德沙普尔不再见于史籍。"),
-- Vienna
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "The name Vienna seems to stir up a classical piece of music in the mind at the very sight of it. But the name originates from the fortress used by the Roman legions to defend against the German tribes."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "维也纳这个名字似乎一看到就能在脑海里激起一曲古典乐。但是这个名字起源于罗马军团防御日耳曼人的要塞。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "After the collapse of Rome, the region of Vienna, like much of Europe, changed hands through the rise and fall of various ethnic regimes. In 955 the German king Otto I defeated the Magyars at Augsburg, putting an end to their rule in central Europe, and in 976 the Babenberg dynasty, the first dynasty of the Austrian margraviate, was founded and Vienna entered its medieval period."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "在罗马崩溃之后，维也纳所在地区也跟欧洲大部分地区一样，在各个民族政权的治乱兴衰中辗转易主。到公元955年德意志王奥托一世在奥格斯堡大破马札尔人，终结了马札尔人在中欧的统治。976年奥地利侯国的第一个王朝巴本堡王朝建立，维也纳进入了她的中世纪时期。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "In 1155, Margrave Heinrich II of Austria made Vienna his capital, and a year later Austria became a duchy. Vienna's strong trading position on the Danube led to the development of her commercial economy and she gradually became one of the most important cities within the Holy Roman Empire."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "1155年，奥地利侯爵海因里希二世定都维也纳，一年后奥地利成为了一个大公国。维也纳在多瑙河上有力的贸易地位使她的商业经济不断发展，逐步成为了神圣罗马帝国内最重要的城市之一。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "In 1278 Rudolf I of the Habsburgs became Archduke of Austria, starting the Habsburg dynasty in Austria, which was undoubtedly the most important period in the history of Vienna. After battles with Bohemia and Hungary, Vienna became the political centre of the Habsburgs and defended itself against Ottoman attacks. The Habsburgs dominated Europe for hundreds of years, ruling Spain, the entire Holy Roman Empire and the world for a time."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "1278年，哈布斯堡家族的鲁道夫一世成为奥地利大公，开启了奥地利的哈布斯堡王朝，这无疑是维也纳历史上最重要的时期。在与波西米亚、匈牙利的争霸之后，维也纳成为哈布斯堡家族的政治中心，并且抵御了奥斯曼的攻击。哈布斯堡家族权倾欧陆数百年，一度统治西班牙、整个神圣罗马帝国并籍此影响全世界。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "During the Habsburg era, when the Holy Roman Empire and Austria-Hungary ruled in succession, Vienna was undoubtedly the most important cultural and artistic centre in Europe. Franz Joseph Haydn, Antonio Salieri, Wolfgang Amadeus Mozart, Ludwig van Beethoven and Franz Schubert were just some of the musicians who brought classical music to its peak here."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "在哈布斯堡先后统治神圣罗马帝国和奥匈帝国的时代，维也纳无疑是欧洲最重要的文化艺术中心。弗朗茨·约瑟夫·海顿、安东尼奥·萨列里、沃尔夫冈·阿玛多伊斯·莫扎特、路德维希·凡·贝多芬和弗朗茨·舒伯特等等音乐家在此将古典乐推向巅峰。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "Although Napoleon smashed the Holy Roman Empire in one fell swoop, Napoleon's defeat allowed Metternich of Austria to construct the Viennese system, which continued the balance of power in Europe for some time. By 1867, after Emperor Franz Joseph I of Austria established the Austro-Hungarian Empire, Vienna had again become the centre of modernist literature."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "虽然拿破仑一举打碎了神圣罗马帝国，但是拿破仑的失败使得奥地利的梅特涅得以构建起维也纳体系，延续了欧洲一段时间的势力均衡。到1867年，奥地利皇帝弗朗茨·约瑟夫一世建立奥匈帝国之后，维也纳又成为现代主义文艺的中心。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7", "ienna's glorious concert halls and beautiful buildings will always be the symbols of a golden period in the history of human culture, and the legends continue ......"),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VIENNA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7", "维也纳各个金碧辉煌的音乐大厅、美轮美奂的各色建筑永远是人类文化史上一段黄金时期最为耀眼的符号，这些传奇还在继续……"),
-- Volsinii
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "The Etruscans are an ancient people of Northern Italy, unique in that they speak a Tyrrhenian language, which sets them apart from any Indo-European people. Their origins are unknown, but it is certain that they arrived in Europe before Indo-European speaking peoples such as the Latins did."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "伊特拉斯坎是北意大利的古老民族，其独特之处在于，他们使用的是第勒尼安语系的语言，这使他们有别于任何印欧民族。他们的来源未知，但是可以肯定的是他们在拉丁人等印欧语系民族到达欧洲之前已经到达了欧洲。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "Etruscan Volsinii (Velzna or Velusna; or sometimes in Latin Volsinii Veteres – Old Volsinii) appears to have been one of the most powerful cities of Etruria, the cult centre of the god Voltumna, and was doubtless one of the 12 which formed the Etruscan confederation, as Volsinii is designated by Livy and Valerius Maximus as one of the capita Etruriae ('heads of Etruria'). It is described by Juvenal as seated among well-wooded hills."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "伊特拉斯坎人的沃尔西尼是伊特鲁里亚最强大的城市之一，是沃尔图姆那神的崇拜中心，而且可以确信是组成伊特鲁里亚联盟的12个城市之一，因为沃尔西尼被李维和瓦勒留·马克西姆指定为Capita Etruriae（“伊特鲁里亚之首”）中的一员。尤维纳利斯将其描述为坐落在树木茂盛的山丘中。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "Volsinii first appears in history after the fall of Veii (396 BC). The Volsinienses, in conjunction with the Salpinates, taking advantage of a famine and pestilence which had desolated Rome, made incursions into the Roman territory in 391 BC. They were defeated, and 8,000 of them were taken prisoner. However, they purchased a twenty-year truce in exchange for returning the booty they had taken, and furnishing the pay of the Roman army for a year."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "沃尔西尼第一次出现在历史上是在维爱陷落之后（公元前396年）。伊特鲁里亚城邦沃尔西尼与萨尔宾那一起，利用罗马的饥荒和瘟疫，在公元前391年入侵罗马领土。他们被打败了，其中8000人被俘虏。然而，他们归还了他们所夺取的战利品以换取二十年的休战期，以换取，并提供罗马军队一年的军饷 。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "They appear next in 310 BC, when, in common with the rest of the Etruscan cities, except Arretium (modern Arezzo), they took part in the siege of Sutrium (modern Sutri), a city in alliance with Rome.This war was terminated by the defeat of the Etruscans at the First Battle of Lake Vadimo (310 BC), a major blow to their power.Three years afterwards the consul Publius Decius Mus captured several of the Volsinian fortresses.In 295 BC, Lucius Postumius Megellus ravaged their territory and defeated them under the walls of their own city, slaying 2,800 of them. Consequently they, together with Perusia (modern Perugia) and Arretium, purchased a forty-year peace by paying a heavy fine."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "他们下一次出现在公元前310年，当时他们与除阿雷提乌姆（今阿雷佐）之外的其他伊特鲁里亚城市一样，参加了对与罗马结盟的苏特里姆（今苏特里）的围攻。这场战争以伊特鲁里亚人在瓦迪莫湖第一次战役（公元前310年）中的失败而告终，对他们的力量是一个重大打击。三年后，执政官普布利乌斯·德西乌斯·穆斯攻占了沃尔西尼的几个要塞。公元前295年，卢修斯·波斯图米乌斯·梅杰勒斯蹂躏了他们的领土，在他们自己城市的城墙下击败了他们，杀死了2800人。因此，他们与佩鲁西亚（今佩鲁贾）和阿雷提乌姆一起，通过缴纳重金购买了四十年的和平。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "Not more than fourteen years, however, had elapsed, when, with their allies the Vulcientes, they again took up arms against Rome. But this attempt ended in their final subjugation in 280 BC.Pliny tells an absurd story, taken from the Greek writer Metrodorus of Scepsis, that the object of the Romans in capturing Volsinii was to make themselves masters of 2,000 statues which it contained. The story, however, suffices to show that the Volsinians had attained great wealth, luxury, and art. This is confirmed by Valerius Maximus, who also adds that this luxury was the cause of their ruin, by making them so indolent that they at length allowed the administration of their commonwealth to be usurped by slaves."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "然而，不到14年后，他们就与他们的盟友福尔善特一起，再次拿起武器反对罗马。普林尼讲述过一个荒谬的故事，这个故事取自希腊作家斯科皮西斯的美特罗杜卢，说罗马人占领沃尔西尼的目的是为了获取他们的200座神像。然而，这个故事足以说明沃尔西尼人已经拥有了大量的的财富、奢侈品和艺术。瓦勒留·马克西姆斯证实了这一点，他还补充说，这种奢侈是他们毁灭的原因，他们如此懒散，以至于最后他们的联邦管理权被奴隶们篡夺了。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "The attempted revolution apparently began with the admission of freedmen into the army, which must have been in 280 BC. They became a powerful plebeian class, who were subsequently allowed to become members of the Senate and to hold public office. They seem to have acquired majorities, using them to shape the law. Other slaves were set free; they gave themselves all the privileges formerly reserved for the Etruscans, such as rights of intermarriage and inheritance, and aggressively insisted on them against the will of the Etruscan patrician class. There were complaints of rape and robbery."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "然后沃尔西尼内部又爆发了一场革命。革命显然是从接纳自由民入伍开始的，大约是在公元前280年。他们成为一个强大的平民阶层，随后被允许成为元老院成员并担任公职。他们似乎获得了多数席位，有权制定法律。其他奴隶获得了自由；他们给了以前保留给伊特鲁里亚人的所有特权，如通婚权和继承权，并不顾伊特鲁里亚父系阶层的意愿，积极地坚持这些特权的下放。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7", "In 265 BC, when the revolutionary party began to pass laws limiting patrician political activity, the lucumones sent a clandestine embassy to Rome asking for military assistance. On their return they were executed for treason, but shortly afterwards a Roman army arrived to lay siege to the town. The subsequent conflict was intense; the consul and commanding general, Quintus Fabius Gurges, was a casualty. A year later his successor, Marcus Fulvius Flaccus, receiving the surrender of the town through its starvation, razed it and executed the leaders of the plebeian party. The first display of gladiators at Rome in 264 is believed to have featured now captive freedmen from Volsinii.The Romans rescued and restored to power the remaining Etruscans of Volsinii, but decided it was necessary to remove them from that location to a new city on the shores of Lake Bolsena. The new city had none of the natural defenses of the old one and was not in any way sovereign. The portable wealth from the old city was carried off to Rome.If the old city was in fact Orvieto, it cannot have remained unoccupied for long; however, it never again posed a threat to Rome. The new city soon adopted Roman culture and language."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_7", "公元前265年，当革命派开始通过法律限制贵族的政治活动时，一位叫卢库孟斯的贵族向罗马派出了一个秘密使团，请求军事援助。回国后，他们因叛国罪被处死，但不久之后，罗马军队抵达，围攻该镇。随后的战斗非常激烈，执政官和将军昆图斯·法比乌斯·古尔格斯战死。一年后，他的继任者马库斯·弗拉维·弗拉克斯在接到该镇因饥饿而投降的通知后，将其夷为平地，并处决了平民党的领导人。据信，264年在罗马举行的第一次角斗士表演是由来自沃尔西尼的被俘的自由人参加的。罗马人救出了沃尔西尼剩余的伊特鲁里亚人并恢复了他们的权力，但决定将他们从那个地方转移到博尔塞纳湖畔的一个新城市。新城市没有老城市的自然防御，也没有任何主权。老城的财富被运到了罗马。新的城市很快就采用了罗马的文化和语言。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_8", "The Etruscans were then quickly assimilated into Rome, and the later Roman Republic and Empire retained many cultural traditions from the Etruscans. By the end of the 1 century AD, after the demise of the Rhaetian language in the Alps, the culture of the entire Tyrrhenian-speaking peoples had completely died out, and details of their cultural customs can only exist in the reverie of later generations."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_VOLSINII_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_8", "随后，伊特拉斯坎人很快被罗马同化，而后来的罗马共和国和帝国也保留了很多来自伊特拉斯坎的文化传统。到公元一世纪阿尔卑斯山区的雷蒂亚语消亡以后，整个第勒尼安语系民族的文化彻底灭亡，有关他们文化风俗的细节只能存在于后人的遐想中了。"),
-- Tirana
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "The early history of the Illyrians is obscure, but recent archaeological excavations and linguistic studies have shown that they were probably a people who entered Europe along with the Greeks and Thracians. They operated mainly in the eastern Balkans and north-western Italy."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_1", "伊利里亚人的早期历史是模糊不清的，但是近年来的考古发掘和语言学研究证明他们很可能是跟希腊人、色雷斯人一道进入欧洲的民族。他们活动范围主要是巴尔干半岛东部、意大利西北部。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "During the Roman Empire, the Illyrians were the main ethnic group in the province of Dalmatia, and the Albanians are their direct descendants."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_2", "罗马帝国时期，伊利里亚人是达尔马提亚行省的主体民族，而阿尔巴尼亚人就是他们的直系后裔。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "Under Roman and Eastern Roman rule, a number of castles were built in the area around Tirana. During the Ottoman encroachment on Eastern Rome at the beginning of the 15th century, this area saw its first major immigration."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_3", "在罗马和东罗马的统治之下，地拉那一带的地区建立过一些城堡。在15世纪初奥斯曼蚕食东罗马的过程中，这一地区迎来了第一次大规模的外来移民。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "In 1443, the Albanian national hero Skanderbeg rose up against the Ottomans, and this is one of the most glorious episodes in Albanian history. As a young man, Skanderbeg was a hostage at the Ottoman court and became an Ottoman officer. When the Hungarian army led by Hunyadi János fought against the Ottomans, he took advantage of the void in the Ottoman rear to return to Albania, declare Albanian independence, convert himself to Christianity and make contact with the Christian forces around Hungary and Naples to resist the Ottomans. He is a beacon of Albanian history, and even though the Albanians have since become more Islamic, he is still revered as a national hero and his double-headed eagle flag has become the national symbol of Albania."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_4", "1443年阿尔巴尼亚民族英雄斯坎德培起兵反抗奥斯曼是阿尔巴尼亚历史上浓墨重彩的一笔。斯坎德培年轻时在奥斯曼宫廷做人质，成为一名奥斯曼军官。当匈雅提·亚诺什带领的匈牙利军队与奥斯曼交战时，他利用奥斯曼后方空虚的机会回到阿尔巴尼亚，宣布阿尔巴尼亚独立，他本人皈依基督教，并且与匈牙利，那不勒斯等周围的基督教力量取得联系，坚决抵抗奥斯曼。他是阿尔巴尼亚历史上的明灯，即便是后来阿尔巴尼亚人多信仰伊斯兰教，他仍然被尊为民族英雄，他的双头鹰旗也成为了阿尔巴尼亚的民族象征。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "The present-day city of Tirana was founded around 1614 under the Ottomans, when an Ottoman general, the lord Sulejman Bargjini Pasha, ordered the establishment of a bazaar, some mills, a mosque (today known as the Sulejman Pasha Mosque) and a Turkish bath. Because of its convenient commercial location, more and more immigrants came to settle here, and in 1807 Tirana became the regional capital. In 1912 Albania became independent, but in 1939 Fascist Italy occupied the country again."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_5", "今日地拉那城建于奥斯曼治下的1614年左右，当时一位奥斯曼将军、领主苏莱曼·巴金尼帕夏下令在此建立了一个巴扎市场、一些磨坊、一座清真寺（今天被称为苏莱曼帕夏清真寺）和一座土耳其浴场。因为商业位置便利，越来越多的移民来到这里定居。1807年，地拉那成为了地区首府。随着民族主义在欧洲的传播，阿尔巴尼亚的民族意识开始觉醒，地拉那开始出现教授阿尔巴尼亚语的学校，一些民族主义性质的团体开始集结。1912年阿尔巴尼亚独立，但是1939年法西斯意大利又占领了阿尔巴尼亚。"),
("en_US", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "In 1946, the People's Republic of Albania was established after Enver Hoxha's Communist Party of Albania led the liberation of Albania. Hoxha's unique position in the international communist movement of the 20th century, with his strong support for Stalin and his insistence on constant class struggle, yet his cult of the individual, made him far more famous and controversial in the international communist movement than Albania. Convinced that a third world war was inevitable, Hoxha built some 170,000 bunkers during his reign, a heavy burden for a small country like Albania and far more than it needed for its defence. Today, most of these bunkers are abandoned. They stand quietly in the poor Albanian countryside, remembering that wild era of the Cold War when all mankind was at war."),
("zh_Hans_CN", "LOC_PEDIA_CITYSTATES_PAGE_CIVILIZATION_CSD_TIRANA_CHAPTER_HISTORY_PARA_6", "1946年，恩维尔·霍查的阿尔巴尼亚共产党领导了阿尔巴尼亚的解放之后，成立了阿尔巴尼亚人民共和国。霍查在20世纪的国际共产主义运动中的地位十分独特，他坚决拥护斯大林，又坚持不断的阶级斗争，却大搞个人崇拜，这使他在国际共产主义运动中的名声和争议大的远远超过了阿尔巴尼亚的影响力。霍查坚信第三次世界大战必然到来，在位期间修建了约17万座碉堡，这对阿尔巴尼亚这个小国来说是个沉重的负担，也远远超过了其国防需要。今天，这些碉堡大多废弃。在阿尔巴尼亚贫困的乡间静静的伫立着，铭记着冷战那个全人类的狂飙时代。");